136/*!
137 The standard OpenCV exception class.
138 Instances of the class are thrown by various functions and methods in the case of critical errors.
139 */
140class CV_EXPORTS Exception : public std::exception
141{
142public:
143 /*!
144 Default constructor
145 */
146 Exception();
147 /*!
148 Full constructor. Normally the constuctor is not called explicitly.
149 Instead, the macros CV_Error(), CV_Error_() and CV_Assert() are used.
150 */
151 Exception(int _code, const string& _err, const string& _func, const string& _file, int _line);
152 virtual ~Exception() throw();
153
154 /*!
155 \return the error description and the context as a text string.
156 */
157 virtual const char *what() const throw();
158 void formatMessage();
159
160 string msg; ///< the formatted error message
161
162 int code; ///< error code @see CVStatus
163 string err; ///< error description
164 string func; ///< function name. Available only when the compiler supports getting it
165 string file; ///< source file name where the error has occured
166 int line; ///< line number in the source file where the error has occured
167};

170//! Signals an error and raises the exception.
171
172/*!
173 By default the function prints information about the error to stderr,
174 then it either stops if setBreakOnError() had been called before or raises the exception.
175 It is possible to alternate error processing by using redirectError().
176
177 \param exc the exception raisen.
178 */
179CV_EXPORTS void error( const Exception& exc );

181//! Sets/resets the break-on-error mode.
182
183/*!
184 When the break-on-error mode is set, the default error handler
185 issues a hardware exception, which can make debugging more convenient.
186
187 \return the previous state
188 */
189CV_EXPORTS bool setBreakOnError(bool flag);

191typedef int (CV_CDECL *ErrorCallback)( int status, const char* func_name,
192 const char* err_msg, const char* file_name,
193 int line, void* userdata );

195//! Sets the new error handler and the optional user data.
196
197/*!
198 The function sets the new error handler, called from cv::error().
199
200 \param errCallback the new error handler. If NULL, the default error handler is used.
201 \param userdata the optional user data pointer, passed to the callback.
202 \param prevUserdata the optional output parameter where the previous user data pointer is stored
203
204 \return the previous error handler

206CV_EXPORTS ErrorCallback redirectError( ErrorCallback errCallback,

236//! Returns the number of ticks.
237
238/*!
239 The function returns the number of ticks since the certain event (e.g. when the machine was turned on).
240 It can be used to initialize cv::RNG or to measure a function execution time by reading the tick count
241 before and after the function call. The granularity of ticks depends on the hardware and OS used. Use
242 cv::getTickFrequency() to convert ticks to seconds.
243*/
244CV_EXPORTS_W int64 getTickCount();
245
246/*!
247 Returns the number of ticks per seconds.
248
249 The function returns the number of ticks (as returned by cv::getTickCount()) per second.
250 The following code computes the execution time in milliseconds:
251
252 \code
253 double exec_time = (double)getTickCount();
254 // do something ...
255 exec_time = ((double)getTickCount() - exec_time)*1000./getTickFrequency();
256 \endcode
257*/
258CV_EXPORTS_W double getTickFrequency();
259
260/*!
261 Returns the number of CPU ticks.
262
263 On platforms where the feature is available, the function returns the number of CPU ticks
264 since the certain event (normally, the system power-on moment). Using this function
265 one can accurately measure the execution time of very small code fragments,
266 for which cv::getTickCount() granularity is not enough.
267*/
268CV_EXPORTS_W int64 getCPUTickCount();

270/*!
271 Returns SSE etc. support status
272
273 The function returns true if certain hardware features are available.
274 Currently, the following features are recognized:
275 - CV_CPU_MMX - MMX
276 - CV_CPU_SSE - SSE
277 - CV_CPU_SSE2 - SSE 2
278 - CV_CPU_SSE3 - SSE 3
279 - CV_CPU_SSSE3 - SSSE 3
280 - CV_CPU_SSE4_1 - SSE 4.1
281 - CV_CPU_SSE4_2 - SSE 4.2
282 - CV_CPU_POPCNT - POPCOUNT
283 - CV_CPU_AVX - AVX
284 - CV_CPU_AVX2 - AVX2
285
286 \note {Note that the function output is not static. Once you called cv::useOptimized(false),
287 most of the hardware acceleration is disabled and thus the function will returns false,
288 until you call cv::useOptimized(true)}
289*/
290CV_EXPORTS_W bool checkHardwareSupport(int feature);

295/*!
296 Allocates memory buffer
297
298 This is specialized OpenCV memory allocation function that returns properly aligned memory buffers.
299 The usage is identical to malloc(). The allocated buffers must be freed with cv::fastFree().
300 If there is not enough memory, the function calls cv::error(), which raises an exception.
301
302 \param bufSize buffer size in bytes
303 \return the allocated memory buffer.
304*/
305CV_EXPORTS void* fastMalloc(size_t bufSize);
306
307/*!
308 Frees the memory allocated with cv::fastMalloc
309
310 This is the corresponding deallocation function for cv::fastMalloc().
311 When ptr==NULL, the function has no effect.
312*/
313CV_EXPORTS void fastFree(void* ptr);

315template<typename _Tp> static inline _Tp* allocate(size_t n)
316{
317 return new _Tp[n];
318}
319
320template<typename _Tp> static inline void deallocate(_Tp* ptr, size_t)
321{
322 delete[] ptr;
323}
324
325/*!
326 Aligns pointer by the certain number of bytes
327
328 This small inline function aligns the pointer by the certian number of bytes by shifting
329 it forward by 0 or a positive offset.
330*/
331template<typename _Tp> static inline _Tp* alignPtr(_Tp* ptr, int n=(int)sizeof(_Tp))
332{
333 return (_Tp*)(((size_t)ptr + n-1) & -n);
334}
335
336/*!
337 Aligns buffer size by the certain number of bytes
338
339 This small inline function aligns a buffer size by the certian number of bytes by enlarging it.
340*/
341static inline size_t alignSize(size_t sz, int n)
342{
343 assert((n & (n - 1)) == 0); // n is a power of 2
344 return (sz + n-1) & -n;
345}

365/*!
366 The STL-compilant memory Allocator based on cv::fastMalloc() and cv::fastFree()
367*/
368template<typename _Tp> class Allocator
369{
370public:
371 typedef _Tp value_type;
372 typedef value_type* pointer;
373 typedef const value_type* const_pointer;
374 typedef value_type& reference;
375 typedef const value_type& const_reference;
376 typedef size_t size_type;
377 typedef ptrdiff_t difference_type;
378 template<typename U> class rebind { typedef Allocator<U> other; };
379
380 explicit Allocator() {}
381 ~Allocator() {}
382 explicit Allocator(Allocator const&) {}
383 template<typename U>
384 explicit Allocator(Allocator<U> const&) {}
385
386 // address
387 pointer address(reference r) { return &r; }
388 const_pointer address(const_reference r) { return &r; }
389
390 pointer allocate(size_type count, const void* =0)
391 { return reinterpret_cast<pointer>(fastMalloc(count * sizeof (_Tp))); }
392
393 void deallocate(pointer p, size_type) {fastFree(p); }
394
395 size_type max_size() const
396 { return max(static_cast<_Tp>(-1)/sizeof(_Tp), 1); }
397
398 void construct(pointer p, const _Tp& v) { new(static_cast<void*>(p)) _Tp(v); }
399 void destroy(pointer p) { p->~_Tp(); }
400};

404/*!
405 A helper class for cv::DataType
406
407 The class is specialized for each fundamental numerical data type supported by OpenCV.
408 It provides DataDepth<T>::value constant.
409*/
410template<typename _Tp> class DataDepth { public: enum { value = -1, fmt = 0 }; };
411
412template<> class DataDepth<bool> { public: enum { value = CV_8U, fmt=(int)'u' }; };
413template<> class DataDepth<uchar> { public: enum { value = CV_8U, fmt=(int)'u' }; };
414template<> class DataDepth<schar> { public: enum { value = CV_8S, fmt=(int)'c' }; };
415template<> class DataDepth<char> { public: enum { value = CV_8S, fmt=(int)'c' }; };
416template<> class DataDepth<ushort> { public: enum { value = CV_16U, fmt=(int)'w' }; };
417template<> class DataDepth<short> { public: enum { value = CV_16S, fmt=(int)'s' }; };
418template<> class DataDepth<int> { public: enum { value = CV_32S, fmt=(int)'i' }; };
419// this is temporary solution to support 32-bit unsigned integers
420template<> class DataDepth<unsigned> { public: enum { value = CV_32S, fmt=(int)'i' }; };
421template<> class DataDepth<float> { public: enum { value = CV_32F, fmt=(int)'f' }; };
422template<> class DataDepth<double> { public: enum { value = CV_64F, fmt=(int)'d' }; };
423template<typename _Tp> class DataDepth<_Tp*> { public: enum { value = CV_USRTYPE1, fmt=(int)'r' }; };

428/*!
429 A short numerical vector.
430
431 This template class represents short numerical vectors (of 1, 2, 3, 4 ... elements)
432 on which you can perform basic arithmetical operations, access individual elements using [] operator etc.
433 The vectors are allocated on stack, as opposite to std::valarray, std::vector, cv::Mat etc.,
434 which elements are dynamically allocated in the heap.
435
436 The template takes 2 parameters:
437 -# _Tp element type
438 -# cn the number of elements
439
440 In addition to the universal notation like Vec<float, 3>, you can use shorter aliases
441 for the most popular specialized variants of Vec, e.g. Vec3f ~ Vec<float, 3>.
442 */
443
444struct CV_EXPORTS Matx_AddOp {};
445struct CV_EXPORTS Matx_SubOp {};
446struct CV_EXPORTS Matx_ScaleOp {};
447struct CV_EXPORTS Matx_MulOp {};
448struct CV_EXPORTS Matx_MatMulOp {};
449struct CV_EXPORTS Matx_TOp {};
450
451template<typename _Tp, int m, int n> class Matx
452{
453public:
454 typedef _Tp value_type;
455 typedef Matx<_Tp, (m < n ? m : n), 1> diag_type;
456 typedef Matx<_Tp, m, n> mat_type;
457 enum { depth = DataDepth<_Tp>::value, rows = m, cols = n, channels = rows*cols,
458 type = CV_MAKETYPE(depth, channels) };
459
460 //! default constructor
461 Matx();
462
463 Matx(_Tp v0); //!< 1x1 matrix
464 Matx(_Tp v0, _Tp v1); //!< 1x2 or 2x1 matrix
465 Matx(_Tp v0, _Tp v1, _Tp v2); //!< 1x3 or 3x1 matrix
466 Matx(_Tp v0, _Tp v1, _Tp v2, _Tp v3); //!< 1x4, 2x2 or 4x1 matrix
467 Matx(_Tp v0, _Tp v1, _Tp v2, _Tp v3, _Tp v4); //!< 1x5 or 5x1 matrix
468 Matx(_Tp v0, _Tp v1, _Tp v2, _Tp v3, _Tp v4, _Tp v5); //!< 1x6, 2x3, 3x2 or 6x1 matrix
469 Matx(_Tp v0, _Tp v1, _Tp v2, _Tp v3, _Tp v4, _Tp v5, _Tp v6); //!< 1x7 or 7x1 matrix
470 Matx(_Tp v0, _Tp v1, _Tp v2, _Tp v3, _Tp v4, _Tp v5, _Tp v6, _Tp v7); //!< 1x8, 2x4, 4x2 or 8x1 matrix
471 Matx(_Tp v0, _Tp v1, _Tp v2, _Tp v3, _Tp v4, _Tp v5, _Tp v6, _Tp v7, _Tp v8); //!< 1x9, 3x3 or 9x1 matrix
472 Matx(_Tp v0, _Tp v1, _Tp v2, _Tp v3, _Tp v4, _Tp v5, _Tp v6, _Tp v7, _Tp v8, _Tp v9); //!< 1x10, 2x5 or 5x2 or 10x1 matrix
473 Matx(_Tp v0, _Tp v1, _Tp v2, _Tp v3,
474 _Tp v4, _Tp v5, _Tp v6, _Tp v7,
475 _Tp v8, _Tp v9, _Tp v10, _Tp v11); //!< 1x12, 2x6, 3x4, 4x3, 6x2 or 12x1 matrix
476 Matx(_Tp v0, _Tp v1, _Tp v2, _Tp v3,
477 _Tp v4, _Tp v5, _Tp v6, _Tp v7,
478 _Tp v8, _Tp v9, _Tp v10, _Tp v11,
479 _Tp v12, _Tp v13, _Tp v14, _Tp v15); //!< 1x16, 4x4 or 16x1 matrix
480 explicit Matx(const _Tp* vals); //!< initialize from a plain array
481
482 static Matx all(_Tp alpha);
483 static Matx zeros();
484 static Matx ones();
485 static Matx eye();
486 static Matx diag(const diag_type& d);
487 static Matx randu(_Tp a, _Tp b);
488 static Matx randn(_Tp a, _Tp b);
489
490 //! dot product computed with the default precision
491 _Tp dot(const Matx<_Tp, m, n>& v) const;
492
493 //! dot product computed in double-precision arithmetics
494 double ddot(const Matx<_Tp, m, n>& v) const;
495
496 //! conversion to another data type
497 template<typename T2> operator Matx<T2, m, n>() const;
498
499 //! change the matrix shape
500 template<int m1, int n1> Matx<_Tp, m1, n1> reshape() const;
501
502 //! extract part of the matrix
503 template<int m1, int n1> Matx<_Tp, m1, n1> get_minor(int i, int j) const;
504
505 //! extract the matrix row
506 Matx<_Tp, 1, n> row(int i) const;
507
508 //! extract the matrix column
509 Matx<_Tp, m, 1> col(int i) const;
510
511 //! extract the matrix diagonal
512 diag_type diag() const;
513
514 //! transpose the matrix
515 Matx<_Tp, n, m> t() const;
516
517 //! invert matrix the matrix
518 Matx<_Tp, n, m> inv(int method=DECOMP_LU) const;
519
520 //! solve linear system
521 template<int l> Matx<_Tp, n, l> solve(const Matx<_Tp, m, l>& rhs, int flags=DECOMP_LU) const;
522 Vec<_Tp, n> solve(const Vec<_Tp, m>& rhs, int method) const;
523
524 //! multiply two matrices element-wise
525 Matx<_Tp, m, n> mul(const Matx<_Tp, m, n>& a) const;
526
527 //! element access
528 const _Tp& operator ()(int i, int j) const;
529 _Tp& operator ()(int i, int j);
530
531 //! 1D element access
532 const _Tp& operator ()(int i) const;
533 _Tp& operator ()(int i);
534
535 Matx(const Matx<_Tp, m, n>& a, const Matx<_Tp, m, n>& b, Matx_AddOp);
536 Matx(const Matx<_Tp, m, n>& a, const Matx<_Tp, m, n>& b, Matx_SubOp);
537 template<typename _T2> Matx(const Matx<_Tp, m, n>& a, _T2 alpha, Matx_ScaleOp);
538 Matx(const Matx<_Tp, m, n>& a, const Matx<_Tp, m, n>& b, Matx_MulOp);
539 template<int l> Matx(const Matx<_Tp, m, l>& a, const Matx<_Tp, l, n>& b, Matx_MatMulOp);
540 Matx(const Matx<_Tp, n, m>& a, Matx_TOp);
541
542 _Tp val[m*n]; //< matrix elements
543};

585/*!
586 A short numerical vector.
587
588 This template class represents short numerical vectors (of 1, 2, 3, 4 ... elements)
589 on which you can perform basic arithmetical operations, access individual elements using [] operator etc.
590 The vectors are allocated on stack, as opposite to std::valarray, std::vector, cv::Mat etc.,
591 which elements are dynamically allocated in the heap.
592
593 The template takes 2 parameters:
594 -# _Tp element type
595 -# cn the number of elements
596
597 In addition to the universal notation like Vec<float, 3>, you can use shorter aliases
598 for the most popular specialized variants of Vec, e.g. Vec3f ~ Vec<float, 3>.
599*/
600template<typename _Tp, int cn> class Vec : public Matx<_Tp, cn, 1>
601{
602public:
603 typedef _Tp value_type;
604 enum { depth = DataDepth<_Tp>::value, channels = cn, type = CV_MAKETYPE(depth, channels) };
605
606 //! default constructor
607 Vec();
608
609 Vec(_Tp v0); //!< 1-element vector constructor
610 Vec(_Tp v0, _Tp v1); //!< 2-element vector constructor
611 Vec(_Tp v0, _Tp v1, _Tp v2); //!< 3-element vector constructor
612 Vec(_Tp v0, _Tp v1, _Tp v2, _Tp v3); //!< 4-element vector constructor
613 Vec(_Tp v0, _Tp v1, _Tp v2, _Tp v3, _Tp v4); //!< 5-element vector constructor
614 Vec(_Tp v0, _Tp v1, _Tp v2, _Tp v3, _Tp v4, _Tp v5); //!< 6-element vector constructor
615 Vec(_Tp v0, _Tp v1, _Tp v2, _Tp v3, _Tp v4, _Tp v5, _Tp v6); //!< 7-element vector constructor
616 Vec(_Tp v0, _Tp v1, _Tp v2, _Tp v3, _Tp v4, _Tp v5, _Tp v6, _Tp v7); //!< 8-element vector constructor

987/////////////////////////////// DataType ////////////////////////////////
988
989/*!
990 Informative template class for OpenCV "scalars".
991
992 The class is specialized for each primitive numerical type supported by OpenCV (such as unsigned char or float),
993 as well as for more complex types, like cv::Complex<>, std::complex<>, cv::Vec<> etc.
994 The common property of all such types (called "scalars", do not confuse it with cv::Scalar_)
995 is that each of them is basically a tuple of numbers of the same type. Each "scalar" can be represented
996 by the depth id (CV_8U ... CV_64F) and the number of channels.
997 OpenCV matrices, 2D or nD, dense or sparse, can store "scalars",
998 as long as the number of channels does not exceed CV_CN_MAX.
999*/
1000template<typename _Tp> class DataType
1001{
1002public:
1003 typedef _Tp value_type;
1004 typedef value_type work_type;
1005 typedef value_type channel_type;
1006 typedef value_type vec_type;
1007 enum { generic_type = 1, depth = -1, channels = 1, fmt=0,
1008 type = CV_MAKETYPE(depth, channels) };
1009};

1012{
1013public:
1014 typedef bool value_type;
1015 typedef int work_type;

1017 typedef value_type vec_type;
1018 enum { generic_type = 0, depth = DataDepth<channel_type>::value, channels = 1,
1019 fmt=DataDepth<channel_type>::fmt,
1020 type = CV_MAKETYPE(depth, channels) };

1238
1239//////////////////// generic_type ref-counting pointer class for C/C++ objects ////////////////////////
1240
1241/*!
1242 Smart pointer to dynamically allocated objects.
1243
1244 This is template pointer-wrapping class that stores the associated reference counter along with the
1245 object pointer. The class is similar to std::smart_ptr<> from the recent addons to the C++ standard,
1246 but is shorter to write :) and self-contained (i.e. does add any dependency on the compiler or an external library).
1247
1248 Basically, you can use "Ptr<MyObjectType> ptr" (or faster "const Ptr<MyObjectType>& ptr" for read-only access)
1249 everywhere instead of "MyObjectType* ptr", where MyObjectType is some C structure or a C++ class.
1250 To make it all work, you need to specialize Ptr<>::delete_obj(), like:
1251
1252 \code
1253 template<> void Ptr<MyObjectType>::delete_obj() { call_destructor_func(obj); }
1254 \endcode
1255
1256 \note{if MyObjectType is a C++ class with a destructor, you do not need to specialize delete_obj(),
1257 since the default implementation calls "delete obj;"}
1258
1259 \note{Another good property of the class is that the operations on the reference counter are atomic,
1260 i.e. it is safe to use the class in multi-threaded applications}
1261*/
1262template<typename _Tp> class Ptr
1263{
1264public:
1265 //! empty constructor
1266 Ptr();
1267 //! take ownership of the pointer. The associated reference counter is allocated and set to 1
1268 Ptr(_Tp* _obj);
1269 //! calls release()
1270 ~Ptr();
1271 //! copy constructor. Copies the members and calls addref()
1272 Ptr(const Ptr& ptr);
1273 template<typename _Tp2> Ptr(const Ptr<_Tp2>& ptr);
1274 //! copy operator. Calls ptr.addref() and release() before copying the members
1275 Ptr& operator = (const Ptr& ptr);
1276 //! increments the reference counter
1277 void addref();
1278 //! decrements the reference counter. If it reaches 0, delete_obj() is called
1279 void release();
1280 //! deletes the object. Override if needed
1281 void delete_obj();
1282 //! returns true iff obj==NULL
1283 bool empty() const;
1284
1285 //! cast pointer to another type
1286 template<typename _Tp2> Ptr<_Tp2> ptr();
1287 template<typename _Tp2> const Ptr<_Tp2> ptr() const;
1288
1289 //! helper operators making "Ptr<T> ptr" use very similar to "T* ptr".
1290 _Tp* operator -> ();
1291 const _Tp* operator -> () const;
1292
1293 operator _Tp* ();
1294 operator const _Tp*() const;
1295
1296 _Tp* obj; //< the object pointer.

1501
1502/*!
1503 The n-dimensional matrix class.
1504
1505 The class represents an n-dimensional dense numerical array that can act as
1506 a matrix, image, optical flow map, 3-focal tensor etc.
1507 It is very similar to CvMat and CvMatND types from earlier versions of OpenCV,
1508 and similarly to those types, the matrix can be multi-channel. It also fully supports ROI mechanism.
1509
1510 There are many different ways to create cv::Mat object. Here are the some popular ones:
1511 <ul>
1512 <li> using cv::Mat::create(nrows, ncols, type) method or
1513 the similar constructor cv::Mat::Mat(nrows, ncols, type[, fill_value]) constructor.
1514 A new matrix of the specified size and specifed type will be allocated.
1515 "type" has the same meaning as in cvCreateMat function,
1516 e.g. CV_8UC1 means 8-bit single-channel matrix, CV_32FC2 means 2-channel (i.e. complex)
1517 floating-point matrix etc:
1518
1519 \code
1520 // make 7x7 complex matrix filled with 1+3j.
1521 cv::Mat M(7,7,CV_32FC2,Scalar(1,3));
1522 // and now turn M to 100x60 15-channel 8-bit matrix.
1523 // The old content will be deallocated
1524 M.create(100,60,CV_8UC(15));
1525 \endcode
1526
1527 As noted in the introduction of this chapter, Mat::create()
1528 will only allocate a new matrix when the current matrix dimensionality
1529 or type are different from the specified.
1530
1531 <li> by using a copy constructor or assignment operator, where on the right side it can
1532 be a matrix or expression, see below. Again, as noted in the introduction,
1533 matrix assignment is O(1) operation because it only copies the header
1534 and increases the reference counter. cv::Mat::clone() method can be used to get a full
1535 (a.k.a. deep) copy of the matrix when you need it.
1536
1537 <li> by constructing a header for a part of another matrix. It can be a single row, single column,
1538 several rows, several columns, rectangular region in the matrix (called a minor in algebra) or
1539 a diagonal. Such operations are also O(1), because the new header will reference the same data.
1540 You can actually modify a part of the matrix using this feature, e.g.
1541
1542 \code
1543 // add 5-th row, multiplied by 3 to the 3rd row
1544 M.row(3) = M.row(3) + M.row(5)*3;
1545
1546 // now copy 7-th column to the 1-st column
1547 // M.col(1) = M.col(7); // this will not work
1548 Mat M1 = M.col(1);
1549 M.col(7).copyTo(M1);
1550
1551 // create new 320x240 image
1552 cv::Mat img(Size(320,240),CV_8UC3);
1553 // select a roi
1554 cv::Mat roi(img, Rect(10,10,100,100));
1555 // fill the ROI with (0,255,0) (which is green in RGB space);
1556 // the original 320x240 image will be modified
1557 roi = Scalar(0,255,0);
1558 \endcode
1559
1560 Thanks to the additional cv::Mat::datastart and cv::Mat::dataend members, it is possible to
1561 compute the relative sub-matrix position in the main "container" matrix using cv::Mat::locateROI():
1562
1563 \code
1564 Mat A = Mat::eye(10, 10, CV_32S);
1565 // extracts A columns, 1 (inclusive) to 3 (exclusive).
1566 Mat B = A(Range::all(), Range(1, 3));
1567 // extracts B rows, 5 (inclusive) to 9 (exclusive).
1568 // that is, C ~ A(Range(5, 9), Range(1, 3))
1569 Mat C = B(Range(5, 9), Range::all());
1570 Size size; Point ofs;
1571 C.locateROI(size, ofs);
1572 // size will be (width=10,height=10) and the ofs will be (x=1, y=5)
1573 \endcode
1574
1575 As in the case of whole matrices, if you need a deep copy, use cv::Mat::clone() method
1576 of the extracted sub-matrices.
1577
1578 <li> by making a header for user-allocated-data. It can be useful for
1579 <ol>
1580 <li> processing "foreign" data using OpenCV (e.g. when you implement
1581 a DirectShow filter or a processing module for gstreamer etc.), e.g.
1582
1583 \code
1584 void process_video_frame(const unsigned char* pixels,
1585 int width, int height, int step)
1586 {
1587 cv::Mat img(height, width, CV_8UC3, pixels, step);
1588 cv::GaussianBlur(img, img, cv::Size(7,7), 1.5, 1.5);
1589 }
1590 \endcode
1591
1592 <li> for quick initialization of small matrices and/or super-fast element access
1593
1594 \code
1595 double m[3][3] = {{a, b, c}, {d, e, f}, {g, h, i}};
1596 cv::Mat M = cv::Mat(3, 3, CV_64F, m).inv();
1597 \endcode
1598 </ol>
1599
1600 partial yet very common cases of this "user-allocated data" case are conversions
1601 from CvMat and IplImage to cv::Mat. For this purpose there are special constructors
1602 taking pointers to CvMat or IplImage and the optional
1603 flag indicating whether to copy the data or not.
1604
1605 Backward conversion from cv::Mat to CvMat or IplImage is provided via cast operators
1606 cv::Mat::operator CvMat() an cv::Mat::operator IplImage().
1607 The operators do not copy the data.
1608
1609
1610 \code
1611 IplImage* img = cvLoadImage("greatwave.jpg", 1);
1612 Mat mtx(img); // convert IplImage* -> cv::Mat
1613 CvMat oldmat = mtx; // convert cv::Mat -> CvMat
1614 CV_Assert(oldmat.cols == img->width && oldmat.rows == img->height &&
1615 oldmat.data.ptr == (uchar*)img->imageData && oldmat.step == img->widthStep);
1616 \endcode
1617
1618 <li> by using MATLAB-style matrix initializers, cv::Mat::zeros(), cv::Mat::ones(), cv::Mat::eye(), e.g.:
1619
1620 \code
1621 // create a double-precision identity martix and add it to M.
1622 M += Mat::eye(M.rows, M.cols, CV_64F);
1623 \endcode
1624
1625 <li> by using comma-separated initializer:
1626
1627 \code
1628 // create 3x3 double-precision identity matrix
1629 Mat M = (Mat_<double>(3,3) << 1, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 1);
1630 \endcode
1631
1632 here we first call constructor of cv::Mat_ class (that we describe further) with the proper matrix,
1633 and then we just put "<<" operator followed by comma-separated values that can be constants,
1634 variables, expressions etc. Also, note the extra parentheses that are needed to avoid compiler errors.
1635
1636 </ul>
1637
1638 Once matrix is created, it will be automatically managed by using reference-counting mechanism
1639 (unless the matrix header is built on top of user-allocated data,
1640 in which case you should handle the data by yourself).
1641 The matrix data will be deallocated when no one points to it;
1642 if you want to release the data pointed by a matrix header before the matrix destructor is called,
1643 use cv::Mat::release().
1644
1645 The next important thing to learn about the matrix class is element access. Here is how the matrix is stored.
1646 The elements are stored in row-major order (row by row). The cv::Mat::data member points to the first element of the first row,
1647 cv::Mat::rows contains the number of matrix rows and cv::Mat::cols - the number of matrix columns. There is yet another member,
1648 cv::Mat::step that is used to actually compute address of a matrix element. cv::Mat::step is needed because the matrix can be
1649 a part of another matrix or because there can some padding space in the end of each row for a proper alignment.
1650
1651 Given these parameters, address of the matrix element M_{ij} is computed as following:
1652
1653 addr(M_{ij})=M.data + M.step*i + j*M.elemSize()
1654
1655 if you know the matrix element type, e.g. it is float, then you can use cv::Mat::at() method:
1656
1657 addr(M_{ij})=&M.at<float>(i,j)
1658
1659 (where & is used to convert the reference returned by cv::Mat::at() to a pointer).
1660 if you need to process a whole row of matrix, the most efficient way is to get
1661 the pointer to the row first, and then just use plain C operator []:
1662
1663 \code
1664 // compute sum of positive matrix elements
1665 // (assuming that M is double-precision matrix)
1666 double sum=0;
1667 for(int i = 0; i < M.rows; i++)
1668 {
1669 const double* Mi = M.ptr<double>(i);
1670 for(int j = 0; j < M.cols; j++)
1671 sum += std::max(Mi[j], 0.);
1672 }
1673 \endcode
1674
1675 Some operations, like the above one, do not actually depend on the matrix shape,
1676 they just process elements of a matrix one by one (or elements from multiple matrices
1677 that are sitting in the same place, e.g. matrix addition). Such operations are called
1678 element-wise and it makes sense to check whether all the input/output matrices are continuous,
1679 i.e. have no gaps in the end of each row, and if yes, process them as a single long row:
1680
1681 \code
1682 // compute sum of positive matrix elements, optimized variant
1683 double sum=0;
1684 int cols = M.cols, rows = M.rows;
1685 if(M.isContinuous())
1686 {
1687 cols *= rows;
1688 rows = 1;
1689 }
1690 for(int i = 0; i < rows; i++)
1691 {
1692 const double* Mi = M.ptr<double>(i);
1693 for(int j = 0; j < cols; j++)
1694 sum += std::max(Mi[j], 0.);
1695 }
1696 \endcode
1697 in the case of continuous matrix the outer loop body will be executed just once,
1698 so the overhead will be smaller, which will be especially noticeable in the case of small matrices.
1699
1700 Finally, there are STL-style iterators that are smart enough to skip gaps between successive rows:
1701 \code
1702 // compute sum of positive matrix elements, iterator-based variant
1703 double sum=0;
1704 MatConstIterator_<double> it = M.begin<double>(), it_end = M.end<double>();
1705 for(; it != it_end; ++it)
1706 sum += std::max(*it, 0.);
1707 \endcode
1708
1709 The matrix iterators are random-access iterators, so they can be passed
1710 to any STL algorithm, including std::sort().
1711*/

2415/*!
2416 Principal Component Analysis
2417
2418 The class PCA is used to compute the special basis for a set of vectors.
2419 The basis will consist of eigenvectors of the covariance matrix computed
2420 from the input set of vectors. After PCA is performed, vectors can be transformed from
2421 the original high-dimensional space to the subspace formed by a few most
2422 prominent eigenvectors (called the principal components),
2423 corresponding to the largest eigenvalues of the covariation matrix.
2424 Thus the dimensionality of the vector and the correlation between the coordinates is reduced.
2425
2426 The following sample is the function that takes two matrices. The first one stores the set
2427 of vectors (a row per vector) that is used to compute PCA, the second one stores another
2428 "test" set of vectors (a row per vector) that are first compressed with PCA,
2429 then reconstructed back and then the reconstruction error norm is computed and printed for each vector.
2430
2431 \code
2432 using namespace cv;
2433
2434 PCA compressPCA(const Mat& pcaset, int maxComponents,
2435 const Mat& testset, Mat& compressed)
2436 {
2437 PCA pca(pcaset, // pass the data
2438 Mat(), // we do not have a pre-computed mean vector,
2439 // so let the PCA engine to compute it
2440 CV_PCA_DATA_AS_ROW, // indicate that the vectors
2441 // are stored as matrix rows
2442 // (use CV_PCA_DATA_AS_COL if the vectors are
2443 // the matrix columns)
2444 maxComponents // specify, how many principal components to retain
2445 );
2446 // if there is no test data, just return the computed basis, ready-to-use
2447 if( !testset.data )
2448 return pca;
2449 CV_Assert( testset.cols == pcaset.cols );
2450
2451 compressed.create(testset.rows, maxComponents, testset.type());
2452
2453 Mat reconstructed;
2454 for( int i = 0; i < testset.rows; i++ )
2455 {
2456 Mat vec = testset.row(i), coeffs = compressed.row(i), reconstructed;
2457 // compress the vector, the result will be stored
2458 // in the i-th row of the output matrix
2459 pca.project(vec, coeffs);
2460 // and then reconstruct it
2461 pca.backProject(coeffs, reconstructed);
2462 // and measure the error
2463 printf("%d. diff = %g\n", i, norm(vec, reconstructed, NORM_L2));
2464 }
2465 return pca;
2466 }
2467 \endcode
2468*/
2469class CV_EXPORTS PCA
2470{
2471public:
2472 //! default constructor
2473 PCA();
2474 //! the constructor that performs PCA
2475 PCA(InputArray data, InputArray mean, int flags, int maxComponents=0);
2476 PCA(InputArray data, InputArray mean, int flags, double retainedVariance);
2477 //! operator that performs PCA. The previously stored data, if any, is released
2478 PCA& operator()(InputArray data, InputArray mean, int flags, int maxComponents=0);
2479 PCA& computeVar(InputArray data, InputArray mean, int flags, double retainedVariance);
2480 //! projects vector from the original space to the principal components subspace
2481 Mat project(InputArray vec) const;
2482 //! projects vector from the original space to the principal components subspace
2483 void project(InputArray vec, OutputArray result) const;
2484 //! reconstructs the original vector from the projection
2485 Mat backProject(InputArray vec) const;
2486 //! reconstructs the original vector from the projection
2487 void backProject(InputArray vec, OutputArray result) const;
2488
2489 Mat eigenvectors; //!< eigenvectors of the covariation matrix
2490 Mat eigenvalues; //!< eigenvalues of the covariation matrix
2491 Mat mean; //!< mean value subtracted before the projection and added after the back projection
2492};

2784/*!
2785 Template matrix class derived from Mat
2786
2787 The class Mat_ is a "thin" template wrapper on top of cv::Mat. It does not have any extra data fields,
2788 nor it or cv::Mat have any virtual methods and thus references or pointers to these two classes
2789 can be safely converted one to another. But do it with care, for example:
2790
2791 \code
2792 // create 100x100 8-bit matrix
2793 Mat M(100,100,CV_8U);
2794 // this will compile fine. no any data conversion will be done.
2795 Mat_<float>& M1 = (Mat_<float>&)M;
2796 // the program will likely crash at the statement below
2797 M1(99,99) = 1.f;
2798 \endcode
2799
2800 While cv::Mat is sufficient in most cases, cv::Mat_ can be more convenient if you use a lot of element
2801 access operations and if you know matrix type at compile time.
2802 Note that cv::Mat::at\<_Tp\>(int y, int x) and cv::Mat_\<_Tp\>::operator ()(int y, int x) do absolutely the
2803 same thing and run at the same speed, but the latter is certainly shorter:
2804
2805 \code
2806 Mat_<double> M(20,20);
2807 for(int i = 0; i < M.rows; i++)
2808 for(int j = 0; j < M.cols; j++)
2809 M(i,j) = 1./(i+j+1);
2810 Mat E, V;
2811 eigen(M,E,V);
2812 cout << E.at<double>(0,0)/E.at<double>(M.rows-1,0);
2813 \endcode
2814
2815 It is easy to use Mat_ for multi-channel images/matrices - just pass cv::Vec as cv::Mat_ template parameter:
2816
2817 \code
2818 // allocate 320x240 color image and fill it with green (in RGB space)
2819 Mat_<Vec3b> img(240, 320, Vec3b(0,255,0));
2820 // now draw a diagonal white line
2821 for(int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
2822 img(i,i)=Vec3b(255,255,255);
2823 // and now modify the 2nd (red) channel of each pixel
2824 for(int i = 0; i < img.rows; i++)
2825 for(int j = 0; j < img.cols; j++)
2826 img(i,j)[2] ^= (uchar)(i ^ j); // img(y,x)[c] accesses c-th channel of the pixel (x,y)
2827 \endcode
2828*/
2829template<typename _Tp> class Mat_ : public Mat
2830{
2831public:
2832 typedef _Tp value_type;
2833 typedef typename DataType<_Tp>::channel_type channel_type;
2834 typedef MatIterator_<_Tp> iterator;
2835 typedef MatConstIterator_<_Tp> const_iterator;
2836
2837 //! default constructor
2838 Mat_();
2839 //! equivalent to Mat(_rows, _cols, DataType<_Tp>::type)
2840 Mat_(int _rows, int _cols);
2841 //! constructor that sets each matrix element to specified value
2842 Mat_(int _rows, int _cols, const _Tp& value);
2843 //! equivalent to Mat(_size, DataType<_Tp>::type)
2844 explicit Mat_(Size _size);
2845 //! constructor that sets each matrix element to specified value
2846 Mat_(Size _size, const _Tp& value);
2847 //! n-dim array constructor
2848 Mat_(int _ndims, const int* _sizes);
2849 //! n-dim array constructor that sets each matrix element to specified value
2850 Mat_(int _ndims, const int* _sizes, const _Tp& value);
2851 //! copy/conversion contructor. If m is of different type, it's converted
2852 Mat_(const Mat& m);
2853 //! copy constructor
2854 Mat_(const Mat_& m);
2855 //! constructs a matrix on top of user-allocated data. step is in bytes(!!!), regardless of the type
2856 Mat_(int _rows, int _cols, _Tp* _data, size_t _step=AUTO_STEP);
2857 //! constructs n-dim matrix on top of user-allocated data. steps are in bytes(!!!), regardless of the type
2858 Mat_(int _ndims, const int* _sizes, _Tp* _data, const size_t* _steps=0);
2859 //! selects a submatrix
2860 Mat_(const Mat_& m, const Range& rowRange, const Range& colRange=Range::all());
2861 //! selects a submatrix
2862 Mat_(const Mat_& m, const Rect& roi);
2863 //! selects a submatrix, n-dim version
2864 Mat_(const Mat_& m, const Range* ranges);
2865 //! from a matrix expression
2866 explicit Mat_(const MatExpr& e);
2867 //! makes a matrix out of Vec, std::vector, Point_ or Point3_. The matrix will have a single column
2868 explicit Mat_(const vector<_Tp>& vec, bool copyData=false);
2869 template<int n> explicit Mat_(const Vec<typename DataType<_Tp>::channel_type, n>& vec, bool copyData=true);
2870 template<int m, int n> explicit Mat_(const Matx<typename DataType<_Tp>::channel_type, m, n>& mtx, bool copyData=true);
2871 explicit Mat_(const Point_<typename DataType<_Tp>::channel_type>& pt, bool copyData=true);
2872 explicit Mat_(const Point3_<typename DataType<_Tp>::channel_type>& pt, bool copyData=true);
2873 explicit Mat_(const MatCommaInitializer_<_Tp>& commaInitializer);
2874
2875 Mat_& operator = (const Mat& m);
2876 Mat_& operator = (const Mat_& m);
2877 //! set all the elements to s.
2878 Mat_& operator = (const _Tp& s);
2879 //! assign a matrix expression
2880 Mat_& operator = (const MatExpr& e);
2881

3202/*!
3203 Automatically Allocated Buffer Class
3204
3205 The class is used for temporary buffers in functions and methods.
3206 If a temporary buffer is usually small (a few K's of memory),
3207 but its size depends on the parameters, it makes sense to create a small
3208 fixed-size array on stack and use it if it's large enough. If the required buffer size
3209 is larger than the fixed size, another buffer of sufficient size is allocated dynamically
3210 and released after the processing. Therefore, in typical cases, when the buffer size is small,
3211 there is no overhead associated with malloc()/free().
3212 At the same time, there is no limit on the size of processed data.
3213
3214 This is what AutoBuffer does. The template takes 2 parameters - type of the buffer elements and
3215 the number of stack-allocated elements. Here is how the class is used:
3216
3217 \code
3218 void my_func(const cv::Mat& m)
3219 {
3220 cv::AutoBuffer<float, 1000> buf; // create automatic buffer containing 1000 floats
3221
3222 buf.allocate(m.rows); // if m.rows <= 1000, the pre-allocated buffer is used,
3223 // otherwise the buffer of "m.rows" floats will be allocated
3224 // dynamically and deallocated in cv::AutoBuffer destructor
3225 ...
3226 }
3227 \endcode
3228*/
3229template<typename _Tp, size_t fixed_size=4096/sizeof(_Tp)+8> class AutoBuffer
3230{
3231public:
3232 typedef _Tp value_type;
3233 enum { buffer_padding = (int)((16 + sizeof(_Tp) - 1)/sizeof(_Tp)) };
3234
3235 //! the default contructor
3236 AutoBuffer();
3237 //! constructor taking the real buffer size
3238 AutoBuffer(size_t _size);
3239 //! destructor. calls deallocate()
3240 ~AutoBuffer();
3241
3242 //! allocates the new buffer of size _size. if the _size is small enough, stack-allocated buffer is used
3243 void allocate(size_t _size);
3244 //! deallocates the buffer if it was dynamically allocated
3245 void deallocate();
3246 //! returns pointer to the real buffer, stack-allocated or head-allocated
3247 operator _Tp* ();
3248 //! returns read-only pointer to the real buffer, stack-allocated or head-allocated
3249 operator const _Tp* () const;
3250
3251protected:
3252 //! pointer to the real buffer, can point to buf if the buffer is small enough
3253 _Tp* ptr;
3254 //! size of the real buffer
3255 size_t size;
3256 //! pre-allocated buffer
3257 _Tp buf[fixed_size+buffer_padding];
3258};

3262/*!
3263 n-Dimensional Dense Matrix Iterator Class.
3264
3265 The class cv::NAryMatIterator is used for iterating over one or more n-dimensional dense arrays (cv::Mat's).
3266
3267 The iterator is completely different from cv::Mat_ and cv::SparseMat_ iterators.
3268 It iterates through the slices (or planes), not the elements, where "slice" is a continuous part of the arrays.
3269
3270 Here is the example on how the iterator can be used to normalize 3D histogram:
3271
3272 \code
3273 void normalizeColorHist(Mat& hist)
3274 {
3275 #if 1
3276 // intialize iterator (the style is different from STL).
3277 // after initialization the iterator will contain
3278 // the number of slices or planes
3279 // the iterator will go through
3280 Mat* arrays[] = { &hist, 0 };
3281 Mat planes[1];
3282 NAryMatIterator it(arrays, planes);
3283 double s = 0;
3284 // iterate through the matrix. on each iteration
3285 // it.planes[i] (of type Mat) will be set to the current plane of
3286 // i-th n-dim matrix passed to the iterator constructor.
3287 for(int p = 0; p < it.nplanes; p++, ++it)
3288 s += sum(it.planes[0])[0];
3289 it = NAryMatIterator(hist);
3290 s = 1./s;
3291 for(int p = 0; p < it.nplanes; p++, ++it)
3292 it.planes[0] *= s;
3293 #elif 1
3294 // this is a shorter implementation of the above
3295 // using built-in operations on Mat
3296 double s = sum(hist)[0];
3297 hist.convertTo(hist, hist.type(), 1./s, 0);
3298 #else
3299 // and this is even shorter one
3300 // (assuming that the histogram elements are non-negative)
3301 normalize(hist, hist, 1, 0, NORM_L1);
3302 #endif
3303 }
3304 \endcode
3305
3306 You can iterate through several matrices simultaneously as long as they have the same geometry
3307 (dimensionality and all the dimension sizes are the same), which is useful for binary
3308 and n-ary operations on such matrices. Just pass those matrices to cv::MatNDIterator.
3309 Then, during the iteration it.planes[0], it.planes[1], ... will
3310 be the slices of the corresponding matrices
3311*/

3364/*!
3365 Sparse matrix class.
3366
3367 The class represents multi-dimensional sparse numerical arrays. Such a sparse array can store elements
3368 of any type that cv::Mat is able to store. "Sparse" means that only non-zero elements
3369 are stored (though, as a result of some operations on a sparse matrix, some of its stored elements
3370 can actually become 0. It's user responsibility to detect such elements and delete them using cv::SparseMat::erase().
3371 The non-zero elements are stored in a hash table that grows when it's filled enough,
3372 so that the search time remains O(1) in average. Elements can be accessed using the following methods:
3373
3374 <ol>
3375 <li>Query operations: cv::SparseMat::ptr() and the higher-level cv::SparseMat::ref(),
3376 cv::SparseMat::value() and cv::SparseMat::find, for example:
3377 \code
3378 const int dims = 5;
3379 int size[] = {10, 10, 10, 10, 10};
3380 SparseMat sparse_mat(dims, size, CV_32F);
3381 for(int i = 0; i < 1000; i++)
3382 {
3383 int idx[dims];
3384 for(int k = 0; k < dims; k++)
3385 idx[k] = rand()%sparse_mat.size(k);
3386 sparse_mat.ref<float>(idx) += 1.f;
3387 }
3388 \endcode
3389
3390 <li>Sparse matrix iterators. Like cv::Mat iterators and unlike cv::Mat iterators, the sparse matrix iterators are STL-style,
3391 that is, the iteration is done as following:
3392 \code
3393 // prints elements of a sparse floating-point matrix and the sum of elements.
3394 SparseMatConstIterator_<float>
3395 it = sparse_mat.begin<float>(),
3396 it_end = sparse_mat.end<float>();
3397 double s = 0;
3398 int dims = sparse_mat.dims();
3399 for(; it != it_end; ++it)
3400 {
3401 // print element indices and the element value
3402 const Node* n = it.node();
3403 printf("(")
3404 for(int i = 0; i < dims; i++)
3405 printf("%3d%c", n->idx[i], i < dims-1 ? ',' : ')');
3406 printf(": %f\n", *it);
3407 s += *it;
3408 }
3409 printf("Element sum is %g\n", s);
3410 \endcode
3411 If you run this loop, you will notice that elements are enumerated
3412 in no any logical order (lexicographical etc.),
3413 they come in the same order as they stored in the hash table, i.e. semi-randomly.
3414
3415 You may collect pointers to the nodes and sort them to get the proper ordering.
3416 Note, however, that pointers to the nodes may become invalid when you add more
3417 elements to the matrix; this is because of possible buffer reallocation.
3418
3419 <li>A combination of the above 2 methods when you need to process 2 or more sparse
3420 matrices simultaneously, e.g. this is how you can compute unnormalized
3421 cross-correlation of the 2 floating-point sparse matrices:
3422 \code
3423 double crossCorr(const SparseMat& a, const SparseMat& b)
3424 {
3425 const SparseMat *_a = &a, *_b = &b;
3426 // if b contains less elements than a,
3427 // it's faster to iterate through b
3428 if(_a->nzcount() > _b->nzcount())
3429 std::swap(_a, _b);
3430 SparseMatConstIterator_<float> it = _a->begin<float>(),
3431 it_end = _a->end<float>();
3432 double ccorr = 0;
3433 for(; it != it_end; ++it)
3434 {
3435 // take the next element from the first matrix
3436 float avalue = *it;
3437 const Node* anode = it.node();
3438 // and try to find element with the same index in the second matrix.
3439 // since the hash value depends only on the element index,
3440 // we reuse hashvalue stored in the node
3441 float bvalue = _b->value<float>(anode->idx,&anode->hashval);
3442 ccorr += avalue*bvalue;
3443 }
3444 return ccorr;
3445 }
3446 \endcode
3447 </ol>
3448*/

3929//////////////////// Fast Nearest-Neighbor Search Structure ////////////////////
3930
3931/*!
3932 Fast Nearest Neighbor Search Class.
3933
3934 The class implements D. Lowe BBF (Best-Bin-First) algorithm for the last
3935 approximate (or accurate) nearest neighbor search in multi-dimensional spaces.
3936
3937 First, a set of vectors is passed to KDTree::KDTree() constructor
3938 or KDTree::build() method, where it is reordered.
3939
3940 Then arbitrary vectors can be passed to KDTree::findNearest() methods, which
3941 find the K nearest neighbors among the vectors from the initial set.
3942 The user can balance between the speed and accuracy of the search by varying Emax
3943 parameter, which is the number of leaves that the algorithm checks.
3944 The larger parameter values yield more accurate results at the expense of lower processing speed.
3945
3946 \code
3947 KDTree T(points, false);
3948 const int K = 3, Emax = INT_MAX;
3949 int idx[K];
3950 float dist[K];
3951 T.findNearest(query_vec, K, Emax, idx, 0, dist);
3952 CV_Assert(dist[0] <= dist[1] && dist[1] <= dist[2]);
3953 \endcode
3954*/
3955class CV_EXPORTS_W KDTree
3956{
3957public:
3958 /*!
3959 The node of the search tree.
3960 */
3961 struct Node
3962 {
3963 Node() : idx(-1), left(-1), right(-1), boundary(0.f) {}
3964 Node(int _idx, int _left, int _right, float _boundary)
3965 : idx(_idx), left(_left), right(_right), boundary(_boundary) {}
3966 //! split dimension; >=0 for nodes (dim), < 0 for leaves (index of the point)
3967 int idx;
3968 //! node indices of the left and the right branches
3969 int left, right;
3970 //! go to the left if query_vec[node.idx]<=node.boundary, otherwise go to the right
3971 float boundary;
3972 };
3973
3974 //! the default constructor
3975 CV_WRAP KDTree();
3976 //! the full constructor that builds the search tree
3977 CV_WRAP KDTree(InputArray points, bool copyAndReorderPoints=false);
3978 //! the full constructor that builds the search tree
3979 CV_WRAP KDTree(InputArray points, InputArray _labels,
3980 bool copyAndReorderPoints=false);
3981 //! builds the search tree
3982 CV_WRAP void build(InputArray points, bool copyAndReorderPoints=false);
3983 //! builds the search tree
3984 CV_WRAP void build(InputArray points, InputArray labels,
3985 bool copyAndReorderPoints=false);
3986 //! finds the K nearest neighbors of "vec" while looking at Emax (at most) leaves
3987 CV_WRAP int findNearest(InputArray vec, int K, int Emax,
3988 OutputArray neighborsIdx,
3989 OutputArray neighbors=noArray(),
3990 OutputArray dist=noArray(),
3991 OutputArray labels=noArray()) const;
3992 //! finds all the points from the initial set that belong to the specified box
3993 CV_WRAP void findOrthoRange(InputArray minBounds,
3994 InputArray maxBounds,
3995 OutputArray neighborsIdx,
3996 OutputArray neighbors=noArray(),
3997 OutputArray labels=noArray()) const;
3998 //! returns vectors with the specified indices
3999 CV_WRAP void getPoints(InputArray idx, OutputArray pts,
4000 OutputArray labels=noArray()) const;
4001 //! return a vector with the specified index
4002 const float* getPoint(int ptidx, int* label=0) const;
4003 //! returns the search space dimensionality
4004 CV_WRAP int dims() const;
4005
4006 vector<Node> nodes; //!< all the tree nodes
4007 CV_PROP Mat points; //!< all the points. It can be a reordered copy of the input vector set or the original vector set.
4008 CV_PROP vector<int> labels; //!< the parallel array of labels.
4009 CV_PROP int maxDepth; //!< maximum depth of the search tree. Do not modify it
4010 CV_PROP_RW int normType; //!< type of the distance (cv::NORM_L1 or cv::NORM_L2) used for search. Initially set to cv::NORM_L2, but you can modify it
4011};

4013//////////////////////////////////////// XML & YAML I/O ////////////////////////////////////
4014
4015class CV_EXPORTS FileNode;
4016
4017/*!
4018 XML/YAML File Storage Class.
4019
4020 The class describes an object associated with XML or YAML file.
4021 It can be used to store data to such a file or read and decode the data.
4022
4023 The storage is organized as a tree of nested sequences (or lists) and mappings.
4024 Sequence is a heterogenious array, which elements are accessed by indices or sequentially using an iterator.
4025 Mapping is analogue of std::map or C structure, which elements are accessed by names.
4026 The most top level structure is a mapping.
4027 Leaves of the file storage tree are integers, floating-point numbers and text strings.
4028
4029 For example, the following code:
4030
4031 \code
4032 // open file storage for writing. Type of the file is determined from the extension
4033 FileStorage fs("test.yml", FileStorage::WRITE);
4034 fs << "test_int" << 5 << "test_real" << 3.1 << "test_string" << "ABCDEFGH";
4035 fs << "test_mat" << Mat::eye(3,3,CV_32F);
4036
4037 fs << "test_list" << "[" << 0.0000000000001 << 2 << CV_PI << -3435345 << "2-502 2-029 3egegeg" <<
4038 "{:" << "month" << 12 << "day" << 31 << "year" << 1969 << "}" << "]";
4039 fs << "test_map" << "{" << "x" << 1 << "y" << 2 << "width" << 100 << "height" << 200 << "lbp" << "[:";
4040
4041 const uchar arr[] = {0, 1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 0, 1};
4042 fs.writeRaw("u", arr, (int)(sizeof(arr)/sizeof(arr[0])));
4043
4044 fs << "]" << "}";
4045 \endcode
4046
4047 will produce the following file:
4048
4049 \verbatim
4050 %YAML:1.0
4051 test_int: 5
4052 test_real: 3.1000000000000001e+00
4053 test_string: ABCDEFGH
4054 test_mat: !!opencv-matrix
4055 rows: 3
4056 cols: 3
4057 dt: f
4058 data: [ 1., 0., 0., 0., 1., 0., 0., 0., 1. ]
4059 test_list:
4060 - 1.0000000000000000e-13
4061 - 2
4062 - 3.1415926535897931e+00
4063 - -3435345
4064 - "2-502 2-029 3egegeg"
4065 - { month:12, day:31, year:1969 }
4066 test_map:
4067 x: 1
4068 y: 2
4069 width: 100
4070 height: 200
4071 lbp: [ 0, 1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 0, 1 ]
4072 \endverbatim
4073
4074 and to read the file above, the following code can be used:
4075
4076 \code
4077 // open file storage for reading.
4078 // Type of the file is determined from the content, not the extension
4079 FileStorage fs("test.yml", FileStorage::READ);
4080 int test_int = (int)fs["test_int"];
4081 double test_real = (double)fs["test_real"];
4082 string test_string = (string)fs["test_string"];
4083
4084 Mat M;
4085 fs["test_mat"] >> M;
4086
4087 FileNode tl = fs["test_list"];
4088 CV_Assert(tl.type() == FileNode::SEQ && tl.size() == 6);
4089 double tl0 = (double)tl[0];
4090 int tl1 = (int)tl[1];
4091 double tl2 = (double)tl[2];
4092 int tl3 = (int)tl[3];
4093 string tl4 = (string)tl[4];
4094 CV_Assert(tl[5].type() == FileNode::MAP && tl[5].size() == 3);
4095
4096 int month = (int)tl[5]["month"];
4097 int day = (int)tl[5]["day"];
4098 int year = (int)tl[5]["year"];
4099
4100 FileNode tm = fs["test_map"];
4101
4102 int x = (int)tm["x"];
4103 int y = (int)tm["y"];
4104 int width = (int)tm["width"];
4105 int height = (int)tm["height"];
